The Anthropic Principle: In science, this concept suggests that the universe is fine-tuned to support lifeâ€”raising questions about why it seems tailored for human existence.
Environmentalism: Some human movements aimed to protect the planet and live sustainably, embracing the idea that humans are stewards of the Earth, not its exploiters.
Social Contract Theory: Philosophers like Thomas Hobbes and John Locke argued that people form societies and governments to protect mutual interests, though they had varying views on the extent of governmental power.
Transhumanism: Near the end of their reign, some humans were getting into the idea of using technology to enhance human capabilities, both physically and intellectuallyâ€”perhaps a bit like your Martian society.
